architecture was originally

00:33:32.520 --> 00:33:35.730
a totally politicized
concept and only later became

00:33:35.730 --> 00:33:37.140
a commercialized one.

00:33:37.140 --> 00:33:38.979
In the '40s and early
'50s, the people

00:33:38.979 --> 00:33:40.770
who were building these
environments really

00:33:40.770 --> 00:33:43.854
saw them as not anti-commercial,
but not commercial.

00:33:43.854 --> 00:33:46.020
They were there to help
people appreciate difference

00:33:46.020 --> 00:33:47.310
from one another.

00:33:47.310 --> 00:33:49.830
Over time, that
politics disappeared

00:33:49.830 --> 00:33:51.300
and you ended up
in the late '50s

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:55.200
at Moscow in 1959 bringing
both this display mode

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:58.120
and all kinds of consumer goods.

00:33:58.120 --> 00:33:59.020
My own view on this--

00:33:59.020 --> 00:34:02.050
I'll just speak my own view,
is that it's a very mixed bag.

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:03.910
On the one hand, I get
frustrated in living

00:34:03.910 --> 00:34:05.740
in a constantly
commercialized environment.

00:34:05.740 --> 00:34:06.760
It really frustrates me.

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:09.159
I would like to be able
to leave that behind.

00:34:09.159 --> 00:34:12.610
On the other hand, I'm aware
that through those commercials,

00:34:12.610 --> 00:34:15.699
I see not only an
array of products,

00:34:15.699 --> 00:34:17.860
but an array of different
ways of living and being

00:34:17.860 --> 00:34:20.219
that might not otherwise
be available to me.

00:34:20.219 --> 00:34:21.969
I guess the last thing,
I have to get back

00:34:21.969 --> 00:34:24.790
to Orwell for just
a minute, right?

00:34:24.790 --> 00:34:27.699
The scary thing is if you can do
the thing that I think you all

00:34:27.699 --> 00:34:31.770
may be able to do to some
degree, which is predict

00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:34.270
the desire of the consumer
before the consumer quite

00:34:34.270 --> 00:34:37.210
has the desire, and offer
the product that triggers

00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:40.090
the desire, then
we're entering a space

00:34:40.090 --> 00:34:43.000
that's a little bit different
than what these folks imagined.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.060
And I'm starting to
be a little nervous.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:46.880
Does that help?

00:34:46.880 --> 00:34:47.560
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:48.469
FRED TURNER: Sure,
you're welcome.

00:34:48.469 --> 00:34:49.570
I hope that's useful.

00:34:54.290 --> 00:34:56.810
I'm curious-- let me
ask you a question.

00:34:56.810 --> 00:34:58.602
Do you see yourselves
in this story at all,

00:34:58.602 --> 00:35:00.060
or does it feel
like something just

00:35:00.060 --> 00:35:01.340
from a really different era?

00:35:01.340 --> 00:35:02.990
I'm very curious.

00:35:02.990 --> 00:35:03.930
Yeah, go for it.

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:04.790
AUDIENCE: I mean, this
definitely connects

00:35:04.790 --> 00:35:06.685
with a lot of what we
think about in terms

00:35:06.685 --> 00:35:09.330
of ecosystem design.

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:11.290
We're constantly
having conversations

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:13.119
about opt-in versus opt-out.

00:35:13.119 --> 00:35:14.160
FRED TURNER: Interesting.

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:15.010
Yeah.

00:35:15.010 --> 00:35:17.900
AUDIENCE: And the tracking
thing at like the Moscow Expo,

00:35:17.900 --> 00:35:21.120
that reminds me a lot of
on online advertising,

00:35:21.120 --> 00:35:24.699
you can track how often people
clicked or stuff like that.

00:35:24.699 --> 00:35:25.490
FRED TURNER: Right.

00:35:25.490 --> 00:35:27.830
AUDIENCE: It reminds me of
like an analog version of that.

00:35:27.830 --> 00:35:28.040
FRED TURNER: Yeah.

00:35:28.040 --> 00:35:29.640
I think it's very much an
analog version of that.

00:35:29.640 --> 00:35:32.210
And I actually think that on
the tracking side in particular,

00:35:32.210 --> 00:35:34.877
there are digital people who are
going to design the computing

00:35:34.877 --> 00:35:36.710
systems that will
eventually become where we

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:39.350
are now who are at this event.

00:35:39.350 --> 00:35:42.320
And for them, I
think that tracking

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:45.750
and pro-democratic activity
are not seen as opposites.

00:35:45.750 --> 00:35:46.850
Orwell hasn't written yet.

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:47.894
It's really like, no.

00:35:47.894 --> 00:35:49.060
We're just going to do this.

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:50.022
It make sense.

00:35:50.022 --> 00:35:51.230
That that's very interesting.

00:35:51.230 --> 00:35:53.090
Part of my goal,
just as a historian,

00:35:53.090 --> 00:35:55.790
is to try to provide
context to think

00:35:55.790 --> 00:35:57.510
about things in the present.

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:00.180
And no one has any time to
really read up on the past,

00:36:00.180 --> 00:36:00.700
I get that.

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:03.740
But it's also like,
this stuff is present.

00:36:03.740 --> 00:36:05.740
Other things that connect
or don't connect here?

00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:06.573
I'd be very curious.

00:36:06.573 --> 00:36:07.240
Yeah, go for it.

00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:09.823
AUDIENCE: I'm an engineer here
at Google, so a former classics

00:36:09.823 --> 00:36:10.546
major.

00:36:10.546 --> 00:36:13.720
And I noticed you were throwing
around the word "democracy"

00:36:13.720 --> 00:36:18.320
very frequently, as if
democracy was an artistic style.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:20.680
But that doesn't jive at
all with my understanding

00:36:20.680 --> 00:36:21.850
of what the word means.

00:36:21.850 --> 00:36:24.690
FRED TURNER: Great.

00:36:24.690 --> 00:36:26.350
AUDIENCE: It's not
an artistic style.

00:36:26.350 --> 00:36:27.940
It's a way of making decisions.

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:28.330
FRED TURNER: Great.

00:36:28.330 --> 00:36:30.730
AUDIENCE: And so the way you
arrange paintings in a room

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:32.900
has nothing to do with
making decisions at all.

00:36:32.900 --> 00:36:35.425
So I am very
skeptical of the claim

00:36:35.425 --> 00:36:38.189
that any artistic
style is democratic.

00:36:38.189 --> 00:36:38.980
FRED TURNER: Great.

00:36:38.980 --> 00:36:44.080
AUDIENCE: In particular,
artistic happenings.

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:47.170
If you take away all
structure all together,

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:48.200
that is not democratic.

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.090
That's the opposite [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:49.090 --> 00:36:50.010
FRED TURNER: Totally agree.

00:36:50.010 --> 00:36:50.380
OK.

00:36:50.380 --> 00:36:51.515
So you and I are
actually, completely--

00:36:51.515 --> 00:36:53.140
I'm going to just
repeat the critique.

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:55.345
Can you hear the
questions and comments OK?

00:36:55.345 --> 00:36:56.590
SPEAKER 1: You can repeat it.

00:36:56.590 --> 00:36:57.140
FRED TURNER: OK, great.

00:36:57.140 --> 00:36:58.070
I'll repeat it.

00:36:58.070 --> 00:36:59.722
So the critique in
a nutshell is I'm

00:36:59.722 --> 00:37:01.180
talking about
aesthetics as if they

00:37:01.180 --> 00:37:02.430
were democratic and democracy.

00:37:02.430 --> 00:37:04.090
Democracy is not an aesthetic.

00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:06.947
It is, instead, a way
of making decisions.

00:37:06.947 --> 00:37:08.530
And some of the
environments that I've

00:37:08.530 --> 00:37:10.427
described as
democratic-like happenings

00:37:10.427 --> 00:37:12.010
are, in fact, anything
but democratic.

00:37:12.010 --> 00:37:12.940
Fair summary?

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:13.480
OK, great.

00:37:13.480 --> 00:37:14.522
I totally agree with you.

00:37:14.522 --> 00:37:16.896
And this is one of those things
where in my presentation,

00:37:16.896 --> 00:37:18.250
I've perhaps been too slippery.

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:20.170
What I'm trying to
give you a feel for is

00:37:20.170 --> 00:37:22.120
what my subjects
thought was going on.

00:37:22.120 --> 00:37:25.090
They did believe that these
were democratizing activities.

00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:27.940
They did believe that if
you got the architecture

00:37:27.940 --> 00:37:30.610
of an aesthetic space
right, it would then

00:37:30.610 --> 00:37:33.010
be possible to make a
new kind of decision.

00:37:33.010 --> 00:37:33.700
Their logic.

00:37:33.700 --> 00:37:34.866
And I'm just repeating them.

00:37:34.866 --> 00:37:36.730
I'm not saying that
this is true or not.

00:37:36.730 --> 00:37:38.650
But these are America's leading
psychologists of the time.

00:37:38.650 --> 00:37:40.233
People like Gordon
Allport at Harvard.

00:37:40.233 --> 00:37:42.160
It's leading anthropologist
Margaret Mead.

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:46.570
They really think that the way
democratic decisions get made

00:37:46.570 --> 00:37:48.610
depends on the state
of your personality.

00:37:48.610 --> 00:37:50.650
You need to be oriented
toward collaboration,

00:37:50.650 --> 00:37:52.910
oriented towards
sharing with others.

00:37:52.910 --> 00:37:54.160
You can't be an authoritarian.

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:55.644
You can't be trying to dominate.

00:37:55.644 --> 00:37:57.310
So before you can
make proper decisions,

00:37:57.310 --> 00:37:59.050
you have to get a
personality oriented

00:37:59.050 --> 00:38:02.110
toward the possibility of
democratic-style collaboration.

00:38:02.110 --> 00:38:03.440
How do you do that?

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:06.520
You do it first in the family
as you raise the child up.

00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:09.130
But then with adults, you
build media environments

00:38:09.130 --> 00:38:12.190
in which they can rehearse the
perceptual and psychological

00:38:12.190 --> 00:38:14.560
conditions that they will
be needing to use when it

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:16.240
comes to decision-making time.

00:38:16.240 --> 00:38:18.980
So Mead wrote a great paper,
which I really recommend,

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:19.490
called--

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:21.031
it has the world's
most boring title,

00:38:21.031 --> 00:38:22.090
so no one's ever read it.

00:38:22.090 --> 00:38:24.240
But it's called "The
Small Conference."

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:26.860
And it's all about exactly
the thing that you describe.

00:38:26.860 --> 00:38:28.630
It's about, how do
you build a room

00:38:28.630 --> 00:38:32.470
and build interaction styles
that will promote a personality

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:36.250
style that will in turn lead
to democratic decision-making?

00:38:36.250 --> 00:38:38.090
Your critique is exactly right.

00:38:38.090 --> 00:38:40.672
So when I went to the
happenings in particular,

00:38:40.672 --> 00:38:41.630
I was really surprised.

00:38:41.630 --> 00:38:44.046
I was always told, these are
the most democratizing things

00:38:44.046 --> 00:38:45.370
to ever hit American theater.

00:38:45.370 --> 00:38:46.120
I got it in there.

00:38:46.120 --> 00:38:49.990
On the contrary, they were
authoritarian wonderlands.

00:38:49.990 --> 00:38:52.580
Almost all white men.

00:38:52.580 --> 00:38:55.840
Women in the shows tended
to be depicted either naked

00:38:55.840 --> 00:38:59.240
or under wet sheets.

00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:01.690
They were horribly misogynistic.

00:39:01.690 --> 00:39:07.720
All of the kind of liberating
politics of the '40s were gone.

00:39:07.720 --> 00:39:08.680
I had no idea of this.

00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:12.475
In the '40s, radical anti-racist
critique in America said look,

00:39:12.475 --> 00:39:13.600
we can't be like the Nazis.

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:15.433
We can't do the racist
things they're doing.

00:39:15.433 --> 00:39:16.760
We have to be different.

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:19.462
Also, a radical argument
for sexual diversity,

00:39:19.462 --> 00:39:21.670
sexual preference diversity,
which I didn't even know

00:39:21.670 --> 00:39:22.210
existed.

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:25.750
I thought the closet ran right
up until 1969 and Stonewall.

00:39:25.750 --> 00:39:27.700
On the contrary, it
turns out that there

00:39:27.700 --> 00:39:30.910
were people writing in '49,
in '48 and '50 saying, look.

00:39:30.910 --> 00:39:32.150
No, we need to open this up.

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:33.850
We need to become
a diverse America.

00:39:33.850 --> 00:39:35.770
Those critiques have
melted away by the time

00:39:35.770 --> 00:39:37.186
we get to the happenings.

00:39:37.186 --> 00:39:39.310
And the happenings without
structure are precisely,

00:39:39.310 --> 00:39:41.920
I would argue, anti-democratic.

00:39:41.920 --> 00:39:43.440
Just right there with you.

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:44.140
Yeah.

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:46.620
Great.

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:47.120
Great.

00:39:47.120 --> 00:39:49.328
I'm just going to repeat
the question for the record.

00:39:49.328 --> 00:39:51.710
So the question is, in
a curated environment

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:53.780
in which every
selection that you make

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:56.750
is nudged and shaped in
a particular direction.

00:39:56.750 --> 00:39:59.630
Not completely determined,
but nudged and shaped.

00:39:59.630 --> 00:40:03.530
And in which your behavior
is constantly monitored,

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:05.037
is that really any freer?

00:40:05.037 --> 00:40:06.620
So I'm assuming you
meant by "better,"

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:10.310
is that really any freer
than the mass media world?

00:40:10.310 --> 00:40:12.780
And if you'd ask me that
question 10 years ago,

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:14.420
I would have said
yes, absolutely,

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:16.400
because people have
some degree of choice.

00:40:16.400 --> 00:40:19.340
If you asked me that question
today, I'd have to say no.

00:40:19.340 --> 00:40:21.320
I find myself strangely
filled with a longing

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:24.320
for Walter Cronkite.

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:26.180
You know Walter
Cronkite, the newscaster?

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:28.220
I was raised in the era
of centralized media.

00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:30.320
We had three TV
stations in my family.

00:40:30.320 --> 00:40:32.160
In my town where we lived.

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:34.790
And as a scholar, I was
raised to critique that.

00:40:34.790 --> 00:40:38.300
I was raised to say, centralized
media, centralized control

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:39.860
produces monolithic opinions.

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:41.390
And that's bad.

00:40:41.390 --> 00:40:45.920
What I see now, on the
contrary, is radically dispersed

00:40:45.920 --> 00:40:48.050
opinions, archipelagos
of opinion.

00:40:48.050 --> 00:40:50.420
Many islands everywhere
producing a kind

00:40:50.420 --> 00:40:52.460
of chaotic lack of order.

00:40:52.460 --> 00:40:54.230
A kind of chaotic
lack of an ability

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:55.730
to make a decision
because we don't

00:40:55.730 --> 00:40:57.720
share the same information.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:00.770
So not only am I bothered
by the power of those

00:41:00.770 --> 00:41:03.550
who curate and monitor.

00:41:03.550 --> 00:41:06.080
I'm bothered by the ways
in which the individuation

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:10.010
of experience through media
makes it more difficult to come

00:41:10.010 --> 00:41:12.490
to democratic consensus.

00:41:12.490 --> 00:41:15.220
So I'm bothered on both counts.

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:15.910
Great.

00:41:15.910 --> 00:41:16.450
Great.

00:41:16.450 --> 00:41:17.530
So let me rephrase the question.

00:41:17.530 --> 00:41:18.710
You're asking a really
important question.

00:41:18.710 --> 00:41:19.960
And if my sociology
friends were here,

00:41:19.960 --> 00:41:21.400
they'd be so happy to hear it.

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:23.260
Because you're asking
about what my field

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:25.750
would call ideological work.

00:41:25.750 --> 00:41:28.180
Do we need to do
more ideological work

00:41:28.180 --> 00:41:30.130
to promote a civic
vision that is

00:41:30.130 --> 00:41:31.656
different than the one we have?

00:41:31.656 --> 00:41:33.280
And particularly, do
we need to promote

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:36.010
a civic vision, something
like the European Union's

00:41:36.010 --> 00:41:39.370
work together, making it
visible to ordinary folks

00:41:39.370 --> 00:41:41.350
so that they can buy-in
to it, rather than try

00:41:41.350 --> 00:41:42.730
to exit through Brexit?

00:41:42.730 --> 00:41:43.570
Absolutely.

00:41:43.570 --> 00:41:44.954
I really think so.

00:41:44.954 --> 00:41:46.870
One of the things that
I fault Facebook with--

00:41:46.870 --> 00:41:49.660
and some parts of Google, but
more Facebook is promoting

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:55.120
the notion that all we need
to be a healthy civic group

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:57.232
is more individualized
expression.

00:41:57.232 --> 00:41:59.440
If you talk to sort of Mark
Zuckerberg and the people

00:41:59.440 --> 00:42:01.148
right around him--
and I know he's easier

00:42:01.148 --> 00:42:03.610
to pick on here than he would
be at the next town over.

00:42:03.610 --> 00:42:04.281
I get that.

00:42:04.281 --> 00:42:06.280
And there's a lot I admire
at Facebook, as there

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:07.238
is a lot I admire here.

00:42:07.238 --> 00:42:10.370
But if you talk to some of those
folks in the middle, I think--

00:42:10.370 --> 00:42:11.950
middle of their
operation, you'll

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:16.760
hear that they genuinely
believe that connecting people

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:18.222
produces a more
democratic world.

00:42:18.222 --> 00:42:19.930
That we need to expose
one another to one

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:21.790
another's views
and simply connect.

00:42:21.790 --> 00:42:24.850
We need to realize as the
poster from the '60s has it

00:42:24.850 --> 00:42:26.910
that we are all one.

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:29.730
I'm here to tell you that is
insufficient for democracy.

00:42:29.730 --> 00:42:31.230
That tends to produce
echo chambers.

00:42:31.230 --> 00:42:32.790
It tends to produce
worlds where we

00:42:32.790 --> 00:42:34.339
hang with those like ourselves.

00:42:34.339 --> 00:42:35.880
The challenge of
democracy-- and this

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:38.460
is the ideology I would promote
if it were mine to promote.

00:42:38.460 --> 00:42:40.110
The challenge of
democracy is not

00:42:40.110 --> 00:42:43.740
to become more expressive
among those who already agree.

00:42:43.740 --> 00:42:47.987
It's to learn to work together
across lines of difference.

00:42:47.987 --> 00:42:50.445
How do you work with folks who
are very different than you?

00:42:50.445 --> 00:42:52.120
How do you make that happen?

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:53.760
And how do you
build institutions

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:58.310
that distribute resources across
differences so that people

00:42:58.310 --> 00:43:00.110
who don't have a lot get more?

00:43:00.110 --> 00:43:01.940
People who have
more can give more?

00:43:01.940 --> 00:43:03.315
And you can actually
collaborate?

00:43:03.315 --> 00:43:04.814
That's the ideology
I would promote.

00:43:04.814 --> 00:43:06.110
I would use the word "civic."

00:43:06.110 --> 00:43:08.954
I think the word "civic"
is under-utilized.

00:43:08.954 --> 00:43:10.120
I love the word "democracy."

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:12.020
I think it's been beaten
down a little bit, so I

00:43:12.020 --> 00:43:13.936
use the word "civic" a
lot when I try to think

00:43:13.936 --> 00:43:15.660
about a civic ideology.

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:16.891
Yeah.

00:43:16.891 --> 00:43:17.390
Right.

00:43:17.390 --> 00:43:17.960
That's right.

00:43:17.960 --> 00:43:18.876
It's not incompatible.

00:43:18.876 --> 00:43:20.390
And I very much
admire these folks.

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:21.889
In fact, I almost
can't write a book

00:43:21.889 --> 00:43:24.962
unless I'm really pretty partly
in love with the people in it.

00:43:24.962 --> 00:43:26.420
I thought for a
while, for example,

00:43:26.420 --> 00:43:28.040
of doing a biography
of Buckminster Fuller.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:29.630
And I got about
five months in and I

00:43:29.630 --> 00:43:31.690
realized he was just
a horrible person,

00:43:31.690 --> 00:43:33.500
and I couldn't spend
more time with him.

00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:35.300
And I felt bad because it's
a really important book.

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:36.500
Somebody should write it.

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:37.790
But I couldn't do it.

00:43:37.790 --> 00:43:41.510
But no, I think Margaret Mead
is somebody I really love.

00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:43.689
And you know, she
back in the '40s

00:43:43.689 --> 00:43:45.980
had a saying that I think
applies right at this moment.

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:50.330
She said, "Were the world
we dream of attained,

00:43:50.330 --> 00:43:54.140
members of that new world would
be so different from ourselves

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:55.790
that they would
no longer value it

00:43:55.790 --> 00:43:58.940
in the same terms in
which we now desire it.

00:43:58.940 --> 00:44:01.400
We would no longer be
at home in such a world.

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:03.530
We who have dreamed it
could not live in it."

00:44:03.530 --> 00:44:05.420
I think we live in her world.

00:44:05.420 --> 00:44:08.600
I think we live in the legacy
of the ideological turn

00:44:08.600 --> 00:44:09.860
that she promoted.

00:44:09.860 --> 00:44:12.200
I'm still partway in
love with that ideology,

00:44:12.200 --> 00:44:15.770
even as I know that it's brought
us things that maybe challenge

00:44:15.770 --> 00:44:17.820
the values that underlie it.

00:44:17.820 --> 00:44:19.000
Yeah, go for it.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:20.130
That's a great question.

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:23.075
So the question was, am I aware
of the sort of long commentary

00:44:23.075 --> 00:44:24.700
forums that are
emerging on YouTube now

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:28.360
with folks like Jordan Peterson,
sort of dark web model,

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:30.760
and how rich and how
thick that commentary

00:44:30.760 --> 00:44:34.180
is as distinct from mass
media commentary, which

00:44:34.180 --> 00:44:36.090
has gotten thinner and thinner?

00:44:36.090 --> 00:44:36.840
Did I get that OK?

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:37.674
Yeah.

00:44:37.674 --> 00:44:39.340
I'm not aware of that,
and I need to be.

00:44:39.340 --> 00:44:40.115
I've heard of it.

00:44:40.115 --> 00:44:40.990
I haven't watched it.

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:43.450
I think watching it is key.

00:44:43.450 --> 00:44:44.534
I have a problem.

00:44:44.534 --> 00:44:46.450
As somebody who does a
lot of historical work,

00:44:46.450 --> 00:44:48.560
I have a time problem.

00:44:48.560 --> 00:44:50.162
I've watched with the web.

00:44:50.162 --> 00:44:51.620
I've been studying
things connected

00:44:51.620 --> 00:44:53.690
to the web since the early '90s.

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:56.840
I've watched things come
and go with great ferocity.

00:44:56.840 --> 00:44:59.352
And so I'm very slow
to react to stuff.

00:44:59.352 --> 00:45:01.060
I have friends who
are always telling me,

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:02.351
you need to try this, try that.

00:45:02.351 --> 00:45:04.250
Some things, like
Reddit, stick around.

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:06.450
Other things, like
Myspace, not so much.

00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:09.980
And so I haven't seen
that yet, but I want to.

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:16.704
I've been struck by the
high-quality small-forum

00:45:16.704 --> 00:45:17.620
commentary that I get.

00:45:17.620 --> 00:45:19.078
For example, on
Twitter I can often

00:45:19.078 --> 00:45:21.250
get very good, high-quality
small-forum content

00:45:21.250 --> 00:45:22.480
from experts.

00:45:22.480 --> 00:45:25.150
I'm also struck by the
great sea of sort of almost

00:45:25.150 --> 00:45:27.210
information that's out there.

00:45:27.210 --> 00:45:29.210
And I haven't found
much in between.

00:45:29.210 --> 00:45:30.280
YouTube's a great case.

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:33.700
My daughter learned how
to do makeup from YouTube.

00:45:33.700 --> 00:45:35.370
She learned from
a makeup comedian.

00:45:35.370 --> 00:45:36.750
It was great.

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:38.410
But I think that's fascinating.

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:39.800
I'll be very curious
to see where that goes.

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:40.300
Yeah, great.

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:41.260
Go for it.

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:42.070
Yeah.

00:45:42.070 --> 00:45:44.560
So is quantum consciousness
and the new spirituality

00:45:44.560 --> 00:45:46.180
the antidote to what
I'm showing here?

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:48.580
No, on the contrary.

00:45:48.580 --> 00:45:52.416
So I've spent a lot of time with
tech folks for a lot of time.

00:45:52.416 --> 00:45:54.790
The mode of spirituality that
you're describing, I think,

00:45:54.790 --> 00:45:58.480
is widely shared in the tech
community and not as widely

00:45:58.480 --> 00:45:59.682
shared elsewhere in my view.

00:45:59.682 --> 00:46:02.140
And I would argue that the mode
of spirituality that you're

00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:04.600
describing is particular--

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:08.350
it supports basically a new
elite, a new aristocracy.

00:46:08.350 --> 00:46:10.900
I'll go even farther
and say that there

00:46:10.900 --> 00:46:13.390
are modes of behavior that
are available to people who

00:46:13.390 --> 00:46:15.550
are super-smart,
super-scientific,

00:46:15.550 --> 00:46:18.250
and super-well-funded that
are not available to others.

00:46:18.250 --> 00:46:19.330
Polyamory is one.

00:46:19.330 --> 00:46:21.310
It's available to
others, but it's

00:46:21.310 --> 00:46:23.360
something that requires
a kind of coordination,

00:46:23.360 --> 00:46:25.960
collaboration sense of
support that's not available.

00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:28.570
Certain modes of spirituality
are in touch with that.

00:46:28.570 --> 00:46:30.520
I'm struck by the
difference between that mode

00:46:30.520 --> 00:46:34.990
of spirituality and Baptist
churches in the South.

00:46:34.990 --> 00:46:35.777
Really distinct.

00:46:35.777 --> 00:46:37.360
I'm not saying that
that's bad at all.

00:46:37.360 --> 00:46:39.400
On the contrary, I'm
fascinated by it.

00:46:39.400 --> 00:46:40.634
But I think it's distinct.

00:46:40.634 --> 00:46:42.550
And I think there are
modes of spirituality as

00:46:42.550 --> 00:46:44.650
distinct from
organized religion that

00:46:44.650 --> 00:46:48.640
are emerging that support a
kind of very individuated, very

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:51.970
tech-savvy, smart kind of life
that you can live if you have

00:46:51.970 --> 00:46:54.490
all the resources that you would
need to be able to do those

00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:55.640
things.

00:46:55.640 --> 00:46:56.770
That would be my--

00:46:56.770 --> 00:46:57.840
I also do [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:57.840 --> 00:46:58.960
I'm glad that you
asked about rhythms.

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:00.580
Because of course,
that vision has

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:02.980
been around tech worlds
a lot in the past.

00:47:02.980 --> 00:47:06.670
The spirituality that you
described animated CW Post.

00:47:06.670 --> 00:47:08.350
I don't know if you
eat Post Cereals,

00:47:08.350 --> 00:47:12.260
but CW Post was the inventor
of Post Grape-Nuts and the Post

00:47:12.260 --> 00:47:13.240
brand.

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:15.869
And he believed precisely
in the kind of spirituality

00:47:15.869 --> 00:47:18.160
that you're describing and
a slightly different version

00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:18.664
of it.

00:47:18.664 --> 00:47:20.080
But he believed
that natural foods

00:47:20.080 --> 00:47:21.880
were one of the keys
to maintaining that.

00:47:21.880 --> 00:47:24.044
He built a whole
community around it.

00:47:24.044 --> 00:47:25.960
There were other groups,
like the Oneida group

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:27.790
in 19th century
upstate New York,

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:29.550
who saw that-- or
the Fourierists.

00:47:29.550 --> 00:47:32.580
I mean, there's a whole series
of kind of groups like that.

00:47:32.580 --> 00:47:35.260
And sometimes, I wonder
when I walk the campus here,

00:47:35.260 --> 00:47:39.770
and particularly when I
see some of your colleagues

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:42.230
in communes where they live or
in new spiritual communities

00:47:42.230 --> 00:47:44.740
that they participate
in, which I do.

00:47:44.740 --> 00:47:47.530
I sometimes wonder if they
are the new Fourierists,

00:47:47.530 --> 00:47:48.440
the new Oneidas.

00:47:48.440 --> 00:47:49.960
I don't know.

00:47:49.960 --> 00:47:50.840
It's a question.

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:53.150
It's a great question,
I just don't know.

00:47:53.150 --> 00:47:55.280
Yeah, I think the answer is no.

00:47:55.280 --> 00:47:58.280
I think that you cannot
have a democratic society

00:47:58.280 --> 00:48:00.950
if the people who are making the
decisions about the direction

00:48:00.950 --> 00:48:03.019
of the society don't
share the same facts.

00:48:03.019 --> 00:48:05.060
And the way that we've
managed that traditionally

00:48:05.060 --> 00:48:07.054
in democratic
societies I think is

00:48:07.054 --> 00:48:08.720
through an elite that
would be in charge

00:48:08.720 --> 00:48:09.680
of certain kinds of facts.

00:48:09.680 --> 00:48:10.850
You would be an economic expert.

00:48:10.850 --> 00:48:12.183
You would be a technical expert.

00:48:12.183 --> 00:48:13.679
You would be a social expert.

00:48:13.679 --> 00:48:15.470
Those folks get together
and make decisions

00:48:15.470 --> 00:48:18.630
and are informed by various
bits of news from down below.

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:20.750
And in turn, send it back
through the mass media.

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:22.910
Here, we can all agree on this.

00:48:22.910 --> 00:48:25.920
In the current condition, that's
not happening very effectively.

00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:28.430
And no, I think it's
very difficult to have

00:48:28.430 --> 00:48:30.050
a democracy in that space.

00:48:30.050 --> 00:48:33.710
I'm hoping that we can
agree on fact again.

00:48:33.710 --> 00:48:37.130
I think it's no accident that
democracy and science tend

00:48:37.130 --> 00:48:40.180
to rise and fall together.

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:44.200
Yeah, we need facts badly.

00:48:44.200 --> 00:48:45.300
Great.

00:48:45.300 --> 00:48:46.107
OK.

00:48:46.107 --> 00:48:47.690
Thank you all very
much for having me.

00:48:47.690 --> 00:48:50.189
I appreciate your taking an
hour out of your day to be here.

00:48:50.189 --> 00:48:52.415
And it's great to be doing--
if you're a historian,

00:48:52.415 --> 00:48:54.790
you spend a lot of time alone
in your room with the past.

00:48:54.790 --> 00:48:56.582
It's so nice to be
out talking to folks

00:48:56.582 --> 00:48:58.540
in the present about the
things that you study.

00:48:58.540 --> 00:48:59.435
Thanks for having me.

00:48:59.435 --> 00:48:59.730
Appreciate it.

00:48:59.730 --> 00:49:00.460
SPEAKER 1: Thank you, Fred.

00:49:00.460 --> 00:49:01.835
Thank you, everybody,
for coming.

00:49:01.835 --> 00:49:03.810
